In order to incorporate time into the hypothesis class, we consider an embedding function $\varphi : \mathbb{R} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^d$ that takes raw time as an input and returns a $d$-dimensional vector denoted as the time-embedding. In our experiments, we define $\varphi:\mathbb{R} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^d$ as a function that maps     t \mapsto  (\sin(\w_1 t), \dots, \sin(\w_{\scriptscriptstyle d/2} t), \cos(\w_1 t), \dots,  \cos(\w_{\scriptscriptstyle d/2} t)), where, $\omega_i = \pi / i, \ i = 1, \dots, d/2$ to the be the collection of angular frequencies. We briefly discuss the rationale for this choice in~\Cref{fig:time-embed-mats}. In our experiments, we use $d=50$.
In the original Transformer architecture,~\citet{vaswani2017attention} use a position-embedding using the frequencies $\omega_i = 1/10000^{2i/d}$ $ \ i = 1, \dots, d/2$. There are two key differences: (1) We use the absolute time $t$ instead of the relative position, (2) We use the angular frequencies $2\pi / i$. In~\Cref{fig:time-embed-mats} \textit{(right)}, we illustrate the time-embeddings when we use the two different choices for angular frequencies. For $d=128$, we find that the frequencies from~\citet{vaswani2017attention} result in slowly changing features which makes it less suitable for our task, i.e., many of the dimensions are constant over time which makes many of the dimensions uniformative for the task. In our experiments, we found out that MLPs and CNNs that use the frequencies from~\citet{vaswani2017attention} perform poorly on the MNIST task for Scenario 2 and 3.
